<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">on at a slow pace singing war songs and rattling the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">chesequois</span>.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[<span class="AddHand-author">W</span>]</span><span class="AddHand-author">hich</span> with <span class="AddHand-editors">[the]</span> neighing and snorting of the houses had a warlike <span class="AddHand-author">appearance</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he weather was fine and we continued until 4 O Clock when the Old chief w<span class="DelHand-author">as</span><span class="AddHand-author">ho</span> acted as Commander passed and repassed amongst us upon a full gallop haranguing which his three sons who were also great war chiefs repeated and we instantly halted, and unloaded the horses.  Soon after a Young man on horseback came for us from the conductor who was already surrounded with the principal men of the Village.  We obeyed &#8212; the conductor offered us a seat near himself the pipe was going round, we partook of its contents.  Here we rested an hour when we were ordered to load the horses.  The Indian who carried the great chiefs great stem of ceremony always had the lead.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he men were formed into a square.  The women and baggage were placed in the centre.  In this manner we marched on<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This part of our journey was considered as dangerous.</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">The</p>

